WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.280
Um, but one, I have six minutes, 55 seconds to get through a whole lot of slides.

00:00:04.280 --> 00:00:08.100
And I get the pleasure of talking about where we are today with the addition of monoclonal

00:00:08.100 --> 00:00:13.800
antibodies, CD38, specifically daratumumab, um, in our quadruple therapy for both newly

00:00:13.800 --> 00:00:18.840
diagnosed ineligible, whatever that word means anymore, ineligible slash deferred folks.

00:00:18.880 --> 00:00:19.280
Okay.

00:00:19.280 --> 00:00:23.840
At this point in time, and again, not to pick sides, but yeah, transplant is a wonderful

00:00:23.840 --> 00:00:25.700
thing, but maybe we can do something without it.

00:00:26.140 --> 00:00:32.600
Long story short is I think our goal should be, and you'll see in the next slide, our

00:00:32.600 --> 00:00:36.580
goal has to be MRD negativity, which to me means we're all looking to try to cure these

00:00:36.580 --> 00:00:37.640
folks as best we can.

00:00:38.120 --> 00:00:40.420
We know when everybody gets there, we know it's not all long lived for everybody.

00:00:40.540 --> 00:00:44.200
But again, as you'll see, as we go through today's, what we do today, therapy session

00:00:44.200 --> 00:00:47.700
versus later on, we're doing tomorrow in the context of curing patients.

00:00:47.740 --> 00:00:49.020
And again, we use that word now.

00:00:49.080 --> 00:00:52.440
I don't think we've done a great job of it, but I think we're getting closer and closer

00:00:52.440 --> 00:00:52.860
and closer.

00:00:53.000 --> 00:00:56.120
So to me, deep, durable responses, meaning MRD negative, meaning curing.

00:00:56.140 --> 00:00:58.300
We can't measure 10 to the minus six, which is what we have today.

00:00:58.740 --> 00:01:01.400
We know it still doesn't mean everybody's gone, but we, no matter what, if you achieve

00:01:01.400 --> 00:01:03.840
that goal, you can do better at any time of disease.

00:01:04.300 --> 00:01:07.260
But what's changed over the last several years is really the addition of monoclonal

00:01:07.260 --> 00:01:09.700
antibodies to CD38 to our induction therapies.

00:01:09.800 --> 00:01:10.040
Okay.

00:01:10.060 --> 00:01:12.180
For both, again, ineligible slash deferred.

00:01:12.660 --> 00:01:15.540
Ineligible patients, there are two members that when I get the opportunity to talk about

00:01:15.540 --> 00:01:18.620
this morning and the studies that go along with it, but again, it's critically in its

00:01:18.620 --> 00:01:23.880
addition to our therapy and the way it works in terms of adding to our IMID, PI, and dexamethasone

00:01:23.880 --> 00:01:26.120
backbone have really made remarkable additions.

00:01:26.140 --> 00:01:28.460
To our therapy and how well we do today.

00:01:28.540 --> 00:01:32.840
There's been a whole lot of studies on here leading to the approval of quads and newly

00:01:32.840 --> 00:01:35.120
diagnosed transplant eligible patients.

00:01:35.440 --> 00:01:36.360
You don't read them all.

00:01:36.460 --> 00:01:39.720
We're going to focus a little bit on Perseus today, but again, Griffin, we participated

00:01:39.720 --> 00:01:43.900
kind of led to this great changes, maintenance therapy, advanced master.

00:01:44.000 --> 00:01:46.580
We're going to talk a little bit about just because of how they're changing, how we should

00:01:46.580 --> 00:01:50.200
think about taking care of our patients against stopping therapy, things like that, using

00:01:50.200 --> 00:01:53.580
risk and response adaptive ways of addressing our therapeutic needs.

00:01:53.580 --> 00:01:55.700
But again, we've heard a lot about this.

00:01:55.760 --> 00:01:59.600
So I don't want to talk a lot about the details these days, but essentially what happens if

00:01:59.600 --> 00:02:04.440
we add daratumab to a VRD backbone, both with induction, with transplant and a maintenance

00:02:04.440 --> 00:02:05.440
therapy.

00:02:05.440 --> 00:02:08.980
And I think we all kind of understand the results of this, which is, Hey, you get a

00:02:08.980 --> 00:02:09.980
lot better MRD results.

00:02:09.980 --> 00:02:14.140
You get a lot better responses at MRD to the minus five to the minus six.

00:02:14.140 --> 00:02:18.780
These are things that are again, remarkably better when you add one drug daratumab to

00:02:18.780 --> 00:02:19.780
these therapies.

00:02:19.780 --> 00:02:23.160
And again, you'll hear from Tom in a little bit that it's not unique to daratumab, it's

00:02:23.160 --> 00:02:25.380
unique to the fact that these are fantastic therapeutics.

00:02:25.380 --> 00:02:31.240
We know that getting to MRD is good, right?

00:02:31.240 --> 00:02:36.240
Whether you're VRD or DRVD in this setting, getting MRD negativity and sustained is a

00:02:36.240 --> 00:02:37.300
really good thing.

00:02:37.300 --> 00:02:40.840
But the deal is with adding daratumab, you're getting a whole lot more patients to that

00:02:40.840 --> 00:02:41.840
end point.

00:02:41.840 --> 00:02:45.980
So again, our goal is to be making these patients have no disease that we can find, whether

00:02:45.980 --> 00:02:48.500
it be risk-responsive or et cetera.

00:02:48.500 --> 00:02:52.760
Again, PFS, we know this, again, all subtypes, we know that it's going to be better.

00:02:52.760 --> 00:02:55.000
And these are all fantastic results with p-values.

00:02:55.000 --> 00:02:58.960
You know, PES ratios that are fantastic.

